From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Daniel Morandini <daniel.morandini@keepinmind.info>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 15:30:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] fftools/ffmpeg_demux: fix copyts MPEG-TS wrap on subtitles
 and sparse streams
To: ffmpeg-devel@ffmpeg.org

The previous copyts MPEG-TS wrap fix kept per-packet DTS/PTS adjustment
when the wrap_dts heuristic confirmed a 33-bit timestamp wrap, but it
adjusted the packet via the existing discontinuity-correction branch that
snaps pkt->dts to the predicted ds->next_dts. For audio/video that snap
is approximately correct because packets arrive at a regular cadence and
ds->next_dts tracks the source within one frame. For sparse streams it
collapses adjacent packets onto a single timestamp:

  - subtitles (especially DVB_TELETEXT/DVB_SUBTITLE under fix_teletext_pts,
    where pes->pts is rewritten to the last PCR and the wrap_timestamp
    state machine in libavformat is bypassed once raw timestamps climb
    back past pts_wrap_reference),
  - metadata streams (ID3) and other low-rate payloads.

A separate problem is that ts_discontinuity_detect was gated to audio
and video only, so subtitles never even reached the wrap heuristic.
Libavformat's wrap_timestamp() handles only the first wrap and stops
once raw timestamps climb past pts_wrap_reference, so without the
heuristic a subtitle stream silently regresses by exactly 2^pts_wrap_bits
ticks roughly one wrap period after the first packet. Downstream muxers
then emit a Non-monotonic DTS warning per packet and clamp the subtitle
timestamps to the last good value, effectively freezing the subtitle
clock and tripping any wall-clock drift detector watching the output.

This patch:

  - extends the ts_discontinuity_process gate so subtitle streams also
    enter ts_discontinuity_detect under -copyts (audio/video gating is
    unchanged for non-copyts paths),

  - replaces the snap-to-next_dts adjustment in the copyts wrap branch
    with a direct addition of one wrap period (1LL << pts_wrap_bits) to
    pkt->dts and pkt->pts, preserving the source's inter-packet timing
    within the wrap epoch for all stream types.

Reproduced with a synthetic MPEG-TS (PAT, PMT carrying a video PID with
PCR and a DVB_SUBTITLE PID with a subtitling_descriptor, twelve PES
packets walking the wrap state machine through the anchor / pre-wrap /
post-wrap / approaching-reference / crossing-reference-from-below phases)
under -copyts -c copy. Without the change ffmpeg emits

  Non-monotonic DTS; previous: 15784527392, current: 7200010800;
  changing to 15784527392

and the framecrc of the subtitle stream shows two adjacent packets at
the same DTS (15784527392) instead of monotonically advancing to
15789945392 and 15789997592. The synthetic fixture and a corresponding
FATE entry (fate-mpegts-copyts-subtitle-wrap) are provided in a separate
patch in this series. FATE passes.

Signed-off-by: Daniel Morandini <daniel.morandini@keepinmind.info>
---
 fftools/ffmpeg_demux.c | 30 +++++++++++++++++++++++++-----
 1 file changed, 25 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

diff --git a/fftools/ffmpeg_demux.c b/fftools/ffmpeg_demux.c
index 99f5cfc2c5..398cbf71cf 100644
--- a/fftools/ffmpeg_demux.c
+++ b/fftools/ffmpeg_demux.c
@@ -234,13 +234,29 @@ static void ts_discontinuity_detect(Demuxer *d, InputStream *ist,
     int64_t pkt_dts = av_rescale_q_rnd(pkt->dts, pkt->time_base, AV_TIME_BASE_Q,
                                        AV_ROUND_NEAR_INF | AV_ROUND_PASS_MINMAX);

+    // copyts MPEG-TS wrap: libavformat's wrap_timestamp() handles only the first
+    // wrap and stops once raw timestamps climb back past pts_wrap_reference. For
+    // continued operation across many wraps under -copyts, add exactly one wrap
+    // period when the packet's timestamp + one wrap matches the expected next dts
+    // far more closely than the raw timestamp does. Direct addition preserves
+    // inter-packet timing within the wrap epoch, which matters for sparse streams
+    // (subtitles, ID3) where snap-to-next_dts would collapse adjacent packets.
     if (copy_ts && ds->next_dts != AV_NOPTS_VALUE &&
         fmt_is_discont && ist->st->pts_wrap_bits < 60) {
-        int64_t wrap_dts = av_rescale_q_rnd(pkt->dts + (1LL<<ist->st->pts_wrap_bits),
+        int64_t wrap = 1LL << ist->st->pts_wrap_bits;
+        int64_t wrap_dts = av_rescale_q_rnd(pkt->dts + wrap,
                                             pkt->time_base, AV_TIME_BASE_Q,
                                             AV_ROUND_NEAR_INF|AV_ROUND_PASS_MINMAX);
-        if (FFABS(wrap_dts - ds->next_dts) < FFABS(pkt_dts - ds->next_dts)/10)
-            disable_discontinuity_correction = 0;
+        if (FFABS(wrap_dts - ds->next_dts) < FFABS(pkt_dts - ds->next_dts)/10) {
+            pkt->dts += wrap;
+            if (pkt->pts != AV_NOPTS_VALUE)
+                pkt->pts += wrap;
+            av_log(ist, AV_LOG_DEBUG,
+                   "MPEG-TS pts wrap (stream id=%d): added %"PRId64" tick wrap\n",
+                   ist->st->id, wrap);
+            d->last_ts = av_rescale_q(pkt->dts, pkt->time_base, AV_TIME_BASE_Q);
+            return;
+        }
     }

     if (ds->next_dts != AV_NOPTS_VALUE && !disable_discontinuity_correction) {
@@ -305,9 +321,13 @@ static void ts_discontinuity_process(Demuxer *d, InputStream *ist,
     if (pkt->pts != AV_NOPTS_VALUE)
         pkt->pts += offset;

-    // detect timestamp discontinuities for audio/video
+    // detect timestamp discontinuities for audio/video/subtitles. Subtitles in
+    // AVFMT_TS_DISCONT containers (MPEG-TS) need the same wrap correction as
+    // audio/video — libavformat's wrap_timestamp() only handles one half of the
+    // wrap and stops once raw timestamps climb back past pts_wrap_reference.
     if ((ist->par->codec_type == AVMEDIA_TYPE_VIDEO ||
-         ist->par->codec_type == AVMEDIA_TYPE_AUDIO) &&
+         ist->par->codec_type == AVMEDIA_TYPE_AUDIO ||
+         ist->par->codec_type == AVMEDIA_TYPE_SUBTITLE) &&
         pkt->dts != AV_NOPTS_VALUE)
         ts_discontinuity_detect(d, ist, pkt);
 }
--
